RIT CLIENT REST API – CONTRACT SUMMARY (LT3 / ALGO USE)

API Version: 1.0.3
Base URL: http://localhost:9999/v1
Swagger Spec: https://rit.306w.ca/RIT-REST-API/1.0.3/swagger.yaml

1. API SCOPE & CONNECTION MODEL

This document describes the Client REST API, not the DMA REST API.

The Client REST API connects to the RIT Client, not the Instructor App.

RIT Client must be running locally for any request to succeed.

Responses are always JSON.

2. AUTHENTICATION (MANDATORY)

Every request must include a valid API key.

The API key can be provided in either of the following ways:

HTTP header (preferred):

X-API-Key: <API_KEY>


Query parameter:

?key=<API_KEY>


Requests without a valid API key return HTTP 401 Unauthorized.

3. RESPONSE & ERROR SEMANTICS

Successful requests: HTTP 200

Client / server errors: HTTP 4xx–5xx

All responses are JSON objects.

4. RATE LIMITING (CRITICAL)

Some endpoints are rate-limited (as indicated in the documentation).

When rate limits are exceeded:

HTTP 429 RATE_LIMIT_EXCEEDED

Response includes:

Retry-After HTTP header (seconds to wait)

wait field in response body

Important Clarifications

In addition to global rate limits, individual securities may have more restrictive limits.

The Client REST API rejects excess requests.

The Excel VBA API queues requests, but this REST API does not.

Code must explicitly sleep and retry after the specified wait time.

5. PARAMETER PASSING RULES (COMMON FAILURE POINT)

DO NOT send JSON request bodies for trading endpoints.

All parameters are passed via query parameters, as defined in the Swagger spec.

Example (Correct)
POST /orders?ticker=CRZY&type=MARKET&quantity=100&action=SELL

Example (Incorrect)
{
  "ticker": "CRZY",
  "type": "MARKET",
  "quantity": 100,
  "action": "SELL"
}

6. CORE ENDPOINTS USED IN LT3
GET /case

Returns information about the current simulation.

Used to:

Detect current period and tick

Determine when the simulation is nearing completion

Trigger forced position flattening

GET /trader

Returns trader identity and current NLV.

GET /limits

Returns portfolio-level trading limits for the current case.

Fields include:

gross, gross_limit, gross_fine

net, net_limit, net_fine

Important:

Limits are case-wide, not per security.

Always enforce limits using this endpoint.

GET /securities

Returns all securities and current positions.

Important fields:

ticker (case-sensitive)

position

vwap

last, bid, ask

trading_fee

min_trade_size, max_trade_size

quoted_decimals

is_tradeable, is_shortable

Used to:

Check exposure

Validate trade sizes

Inspect fees and execution constraints

GET /securities/book?ticker=XXX

Returns the current order book for a security.

Official documentation shows:

{
  "bid": [...],
  "ask": [...]
}


Important:

Some RIT client versions may return bids / asks.

Code must defensively handle both naming conventions.

Used to:

Measure liquidity

Compute VWAP

Validate unwind feasibility

GET /orders

Returns all orders, filtered by status (default: OPEN).

POST /orders

Submits a new order.

Query parameters:

ticker (required)

type = MARKET or LIMIT (required)

quantity (required)

action = BUY or SELL (required)

price (required only if type = LIMIT)

dry_run (optional, MARKET only)

Important:

dry_run simulates execution without placing the order.

Useful for liquidity checks without creating exposure.

GET /orders/{id}

Returns details of a specific order.

DELETE /orders/{id}

Cancels an open order.

POST /commands/cancel

Bulk cancel open orders.

Exactly one query parameter must be specified:

all=1

ticker=CRZY

ids=1,2,3

query=<SQL-like filter>

Used to:

Clean up unfilled limit orders

Prevent end-of-session penalties

GET /tenders

Returns all active institutional tenders.

Fields include:

tender_id

quantity

price

action (BUY or SELL from institution)

expires

caption

is_fixed_bid

Important:

Ticker is not a structured field.

The ticker must be parsed from the caption text.

POST /tenders/{id}

Accepts a tender.

price query parameter is required only if the tender is not fixed-bid.

No market trading is permitted before this endpoint is called.

DELETE /tenders/{id}

Declines a tender.

7. LT3 BEHAVIORAL CONSTRAINTS (API-RELEVANT)

No market trades are permitted before tender acceptance.

All trades must be directly linked to unwinding tender exposure.

Prefer MARKET orders for certainty.

Limit orders must be aggressively priced and actively managed.

All open orders must be cancelled if no longer needed.

All positions must be flattened before simulation end to avoid fines.

8. COMMON IMPLEMENTATION ERRORS TO AVOID

Sending JSON bodies instead of query parameters

Assuming tender objects contain a ticker field

Ignoring /limits

Leaving unfilled limit orders open

Assuming queued behavior for REST requests

Trading outside accepted tender exposure

9. INTENDED HIGH-LEVEL USAGE FLOW

Poll /tenders

Evaluate profitability via /securities/book

Check portfolio limits via /limits

Accept tender using /tenders/{id}

Unwind exposure via /orders

Monitor simulation state via /case

Cancel orders and flatten positions before end

